	let { sdgColor = getSdgColor(16) }: Props = $props();
</script>

<div class="lesson-content">

	<CustomSection title={"(30-60 MINUTES)"} content={"<strong>Materials:</strong><br>Open space suitable for movement and group work<br>Whiteboard or large chart paper<br>Markers<br>Notebooks or paper<br>Pens/Pencils<br>[Optional] Simple, easily manipulated props that can be used symbolically (e.g., fabric scraps, ropes, blocks, signs with keywords like “power,” “truth,” “voice”)"} {sdgColor} />

	<Introduction content={"<p>Begin with an engaging introduction to devised theater.\n<ul>\n<li>Devised theater is a way of creating theater collaboratively, without a pre-written script. Instead, the group uses ideas, themes, images, sound/voice, and movement to build a performance together.</li>\n<li>Think of it as collective storytelling through action, sound, and words. Everyone’s ideas contribute to the final piece.</li>\n<li>Today, we will use simple techniques to explore important ideas about peace and justice.</li>\n</ul><br>Introduce basic elements of devised theater:\n<ul>\n<li><em>Stimulus:</em> A starting point for creation (e.g., a word, an image, a feeling, a current event related to Global Goal 16).</li>\n<li><em>Improvisation:</em> Spontaneous acting, vocalization, and movement to explore ideas.</li>\n<li><em>Physical theater:</em> Using the body to communicate meaning.</li>\n<li><em>Sound and Rhythm:</em> Incorporating vocal sounds, improvised words/phrases, body percussion, or simple rhythms.</li>\n<li><em>Space and Levels:</em> Using the performance area in different ways (high, low, near, far).</li>\n</ul><br>Emphasize that the focus will be on simple explorations and collective creation, not a polished and “perfect” performance.<br>Introduce or reintroduce UN Global Goal 16: Promote peaceful and inclusive societies for sustainable development, provide access to justice for all and build effective, accountable and inclusive institutions at all levels. Emphasize the relevance of these principles to their lives and the world around them.<br>Briefly review the key themes of Global Goal 16:\n<ul>\n<li>Reducing violence and promoting safety.</li>\n<li>Ending abuse and exploitation.</li>\n<li>Combating corruption and organized crime.</li>\n<li>Building effective and inclusive institutions.</li>\n<li>Promoting participation and access to information.</li>\n</ul><br>Connect devised theater and Global Goal 16 by engaging students in a discussion about how devised theater can explore themes of peace and justice.<br>Ask guiding questions like:\n<ul>\n<li>How can we use movement and gesture to represent concepts like fairness or unfairness?</li>\n<li>Can we create a short piece that shows the impact of violence or the building of peace?</li>\n<li>How can we use improvised vocalizations, sound, and rhythm to express the urgency of justice or the strength of institutions?</li>\n<li>How can working together to create theater mirror the idea of building inclusive societies?</li>\n</ul></p>"} />

	<CustomSection title={"Collaborative Devised theater Exploration"} content={"<p>Begin a whole class brainstorm (stimulus) by presenting a series of simple stimuli related to different targets of Global Goal 16. For each stimulus, have students briefly brainstorm associated images, feelings, or actions.<br>Examples of stimuli (can use as prompts or have the class come up with their own):\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Target 16.1</strong> <em>(Reduce Violence):</em></li>\n<li>The word “silence” after a loud noise.</li>\n<li>The feeling of a tightly clenched fist slowly opening.</li>\n<li><strong>Target 16.2</strong> <em>(End Abuse):</em></li>\n<li>The image of someone being trapped or restricted.</li>\n<li>A broken bird’s wing.</li>\n<li><strong>Target 16.3</strong> <em>(Rule of Law):</em></li>\n<li>The idea of a balanced scale.</li>\n<li>The sound of a gavel striking.</li>\n<li><strong>Target 16.4</strong> <em>(Illicit Flows):</em></li>\n<li>The action of something hidden being revealed.</li>\n<li>A dark, winding river.</li>\n<li><strong>Target 16.5</strong> <em>(Reduce Corruption):</em></li>\n<li>The feeling of something being “sticky” or difficult to move.</li>\n<li>The image of a spiderweb trapping something.</li>\n<li><strong>Target 16.6</strong> <em>(Accountable Institutions):</em></li>\n<li>The image of many hands working together to build something.</li>\n<li>The feeling of a building with strong foundations.</li>\n<li><strong>Target 16.7</strong> <em>(Inclusive Decision Making):</em></li>\n<li>The action of many people contributing to a central point.</li>\n<li>A circle of people all facing inwards.</li>\n<li><strong>Target 16.8</strong> <em>(Global Governance):</em></li>\n<li>The image of different shapes fitting together.</li>\n<li>Different musical instruments playing together.</li>\n<li><strong>Target 16.9</strong> <em>(Legal Identity):</em></li>\n<li>The action of someone being recognized or seen clearly.</li>\n<li>A single fingerprint.</li>\n<li><strong>Target 16.10</strong> <em>(Access to Information):</em></li>\n<li>The gesture of opening or revealing something.</li>\n<li>A beam of light cutting through darkness.</li>\n<li><strong>Target 16.a</strong> <em>(Strengthen Institutions):</em></li>\n<li>The feeling of providing support or reinforcement.</li>\n<li>The action of tying a knot to make something stronger</li>\n<li><strong>Target 16.b</strong> <em>(Non-Discrimination):</em></li>\n<li>The action of separating and then coming together equally.</li>\n<li>Different colors blending together.</li>\n</ul><br>Begin guided improvisation and vocal/movement building by guiding the class through a series of simple, whole-class improvisations based on the brainstormed ideas for each stimulus, encouraging both vocal and movement improvisation.<br>For each target/idea, lead a short (2-3 minute) exploration:<br>Examples:\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Target 16.1</strong> <em>(Reduce Violence):</em></li>\n<li>Let’s explore the feeling of a tightly clenched fist slowly opening. Everyone make a tight fist. Hold the tension in your body. Now, very slowly, release your fingers, your hand, your arm. What sounds might accompany this release? What words might express the shift from tension to calm?</li>\n<li><strong>Target 16.2</strong> <em>(End Abuse):</em></li>\n<li>Let’s explore the image of a broken bird’s wing. Find a posture that feels restricted or wounded. How might you move with this limitation? What sounds of pain, frustration, or longing might you make? What single word might capture this feeling?</li>\n<li><strong>Target 16.3</strong> <em>(Rule of Law):</em></li>\n<li>Let’s explore the sound of a gavel striking. Find a still, upright posture. Then, with  a sharp, clear movement and sound (clap, stomp, vocalization), represent the gavel. What feeling does this action evoke? What words might signify order, judgement, or fairness?</li>\n<li><strong>Target 16.4</strong> <em>(Illicit Flows):</em></li>\n<li>Let’s explore a dark, winding river. Move through the space as if you are this river, with hidden currents and unexpected turns. What sounds might the river make? What whispered words or phrases might represent secrets or hidden movements?</li>\n<li><strong>Target 16.5</strong> <em>(Reduce Corruption):</em></li>\n<li>Let’s explore the image of a spiderweb trapping something. Move as if you are caught, your movements sticky and difficult. What sounds of struggle or being ensnared might you make? What words might express being stuck or manipulated?</li>\n<li><strong>Target 16.6</strong> <em>(Accountable Institutions):</em></li>\n<li>Let’s explore the feeling of a building with strong foundations. Find a grounded, stable stance. Then, imagine adding layers or supports with your movements and sounds. What vocalizations represent strength, reliability, or shared effort? What simple word could be a foundation?</li>\n<li><strong>Target 16.7</strong> <em>(Inclusive Decision Making):</em></li>\n<li>Let’s explore a circle of people all facing inwards. Move as if you are offering a movement or sound to the center. Then, respond to what others offer. What sounds or phrases might represent your contribution or your response to others?</li>\n<li><strong>Target 16.8</strong> <em>(Global Governance):</em></li>\n<li>Let’s explore different musical instruments playing together. Each person choose a simple sound or movement rhythm. Then, try to layer these together, listening and responding to create a collective harmony or dissonance. What words or sounds might represent agreement or disagreement?</li>\n<li><strong>Target 16.9</strong> <em>(Legal Identity):</em></li>\n<li>Let’s explore the action of someone being recognized or seen clearly. Start with a closed-off posture. Then, slowly unfold and reveal a unique gesture or movement. What sound or word(s) might represent being seen, identified, or having a voice?</li>\n<li><strong>Target 16.10</strong> <em>(Access to Information):</em></li>\n<li>Let’s explore a beam of light cutting through darkness. Start in a shadowed or closed-off position. Then, with a focused movement and sound, break through into an open, illuminated space. What sounds or words might represent the revealing of truth or access to knowledge?</li>\n<li><strong>Target 16.a</strong> <em>(Strengthen Institutions):</em></li>\n<li>Let’s explore the action of tying a knot to make something stronger. Use your body to show something weak or unstable. Then, with focused movements, show the act of reinforcing or connecting. What sounds or short phrases might represent building strength or providing support?</li>\n<li><strong>Target 16.b</strong> <em>(Non-Discrimination):</em></li>\n<li>Let’s explore the action of separating and then coming together equally. Start with distinct, separate movements or sounds. The, gradually blend them, finding moments of harmony or shared rhythm. What sounds or words might represent separation, then unity and equality?</li>\n</ul><br>Encourage students to:\n<ul>\n<li>Focus on vocal and physical communication.</li>\n<li>Explore different levels, speeds, and energy levels in both voice and movement.</li>\n<li>Respond to the vocalizations and movements of others in the group.</li>\n<li>Keep the focus on the core concept related to the idea surrounding Global Goal 16.</li>\n</ul><br>Basical theatrical elements can be introduced to enhance the improvisation:\n<ul>\n<li><em>Levels:</em> Using different heights to create interest and symbolize power or vulnerability both in movement and vocal pitch.</li>\n<li><em>Pacing:</em> Varying the speed of speech and movement.</li>\n<li><em>Focus:</em> Directing attention with the voice and body.</li>\n<li><em>Repetition:</em> Repeating sounds, improvised words, or movements for emphasis.</li>\n<li><em>Vocal Tone:</em> Using different tones of voice to convey emotion (e.g., anger, fear, hope).</li>\n</ul></p>"} {sdgColor} />

	<CustomSection title={"Connection and Discussion"} content={"<p>Facilitate a class discussion connecting the devised theater work to Global Goal 16.<br>Ask guiding questions like:\n<ul>\n<li>How did we use our voices and movement to represent the ideas of peace and justice?</li>\n<li>Which movements or vocalizations were most effective in conveying a specific target of Global Goal 16?</li>\n<li>What did you notice about how the group worked together to create meaning through both action and sound?</li>\n<li>How can this way of creating theater help us understand complex social issues and give voice to different perspecives?</li>\n</ul></p>"} {sdgColor} />

	<CustomSection title={"Reflection and Summary"} content={"<p>Have students reflect on their learning experience through discussion or writing.<br>Ask guiding questions like:\n<ul>\n<li>How did using both movement and vocal improvisation in our devised theater explorations help you understand the complex concepts of peace, justice, and strong institutions?</li>\n<li>What did you learn about the power of combining physical actions with spontaneous words and sounds to convey emotions and ideas related to Global Goal 16?</li>\n<li>Did creating short theatrical pieces, exploring different stimuli, help you see the challenges or opportunities of building just societies in a new or more impactful way?</li>\n<li>What did you discover about your own capacity to express complex social issues through both your body and your voice in a collaborative setting?</li>\n<li>How can devised theater, which builds from the ground up, mirror the process of building inclusive communities or strengthening institutions?</li>\n<li>What new insights did you gain about Global Goal 16 and the importance of promoting peaceful and inclusive societies, providing access to justice, and building effective, accountable institutions?</li>\n<li>How did the various explorations (e.g., related to violence, corruption, legal identity, non-discrimination) illuminate the diverse facets and interconnectedness of Global Goal 16?</li>\n<li>Did the activity make you think differently about how different voices and perspectives (represented by our individual contributions) are crucial for addressing issues of justice and peace?</li>\n<li>What common themes or powerful messages about building a fairer world emerged across the different improvisations we explored?</li>\n<li>How does a theatrical approach help to humanize the abstract concepts of governance, policy, and human rights?</li>\n<li>Did any particular movement, vocalization, or collaborative moment from our explorations resonate with you personally regarding issues of peace, justice, or fairness?</li>\n<li>What emotions did you connect with during this lesson, and how might those emotions motivate you to take action related to Global Goal 16?</li>\n<li>What is one key takeaway about building justice and the power of collaborative creative expression that you will remember from this lesson?</li>\n<li>How has this lesson influenced your thinking about your own role in promoting peace and justice in your daily life or community?</li>\n</ul></p>"} {sdgColor} />

	<CustomSection title={"Assessment"} content={"<ul>\n<li>Consistent and enthusiastic involvement in all phases of the lesson, including the introduction to devised theater, brainstorming stimuli, guided improvisations (both physical and vocal), and class discussions.</li>\n<li>Comprehension of Global Goal 16 themes (e.g., reducing violence, access to justice, strong institutions, human rights, anti-corruption) as demonstrated through the intention and content of the movement and vocal improvisations and verbal explanations during discussions.</li>\n<li>Originality and effectiveness in applying chosen devised theater elements (e.g., physical theater, vocalizations, improvised words/phrases, use of space/levels, rhythm) to explore and communicate messages related to Global Goal 16.</li>\n<li>How clearly and powerfully the collective improvisations communicated the understanding of specific aspects of Global Goal 16. Did the combined actions and sounds successfully evoke thought or emotion related to the goal?</li>\n<li>Ability to work effectively as a whole class, demonstrating active listening, responsive movement and vocalization, and a cohesive group dynamic during shared explorations. Look for willingness to build on others’ ideas.</li>\n<li>Comfort level in experimenting with spontaneous movement and vocalization, demonstrating a willingness to step out of the comfort zone for creative expression.</li>\n<li>Nuance and depth of understanding demonstrated in reflections, particularly concerning the role of embodied and vocal theater in understanding complex social issues and achieving peace and justice.</li>\n</ul>"} {sdgColor} />

