 Move as if you are offering a movement or sound to the center. Then, respond to what others offer. What sounds or phrases might represent your contribution or your response to others?</li>\n<li><strong>Target 16.8</strong> <em>(Global Governance):</em></li>\n<li>Let’s explore different musical instruments playing together. Each person choose a simple sound or movement rhythm. Then, try to layer these together, listening and responding to create a collective harmony or dissonance. What words or sounds might represent agreement or disagreement?</li>\n<li><strong>Target 16.9</strong> <em>(Legal Identity):</em></li>\n<li>Let’s explore the action of someone being recognized or seen clearly. Start with a closed-off posture. Then, slowly unfold and reveal a unique gesture or movement. What sound or word(s) might represent being seen, identified, or having a voice?</li>\n<li><strong>Target 16.10</strong> <em>(Access to Information):</em></li>\n<li>Let’s explore a beam of light cutting through darkness. Start in a shadowed or closed-off position. Then, with a focused movement and sound, break through into an open, illuminated space. What sounds or words might represent the revealing of truth or access to knowledge?</li>\n<li><strong>Target 16.a</strong> <em>(Strengthen Institutions):</em></li>\n<li>Let’s explore the action of tying a knot to make something stronger. Use your body to show something weak or unstable. Then, with focused movements, show the act of reinforcing or connecting. What sounds or short phrases might represent building strength or providing support?</li>\n<li><strong>Target 16.b</strong> <em>(Non-Discrimination):</em></li>\n<li>Let’s explore the action of separating and then coming together equally. Start with distinct, separate movements or sounds. The, gradually blend them, finding moments of harmony or shared rhythm. What sounds or words might represent separation, then unity and equality?</li>\n</ul><br>Encourage students to:\n<ul>\n<li>Focus on vocal and physical communication.</li>\n<li>Explore different levels, speeds, and energy levels in both voice and movement.</li>\n<li>Respond to the vocalizations and movements of others in the group.</li>\n<li>Keep the focus on the core concept related to the idea surrounding Global Goal 16.</li>\n</ul><br>Basical theatrical elements can be introduced to enhance the improvisation:\n<ul>\n<li><em>Levels:</em> Using different heights to create interest and symbolize power or vulnerability both in movement and vocal pitch.</li>\n<li><em>Pacing:</em> Varying the speed of speech and movement.</li>\n<li><em>Focus:</em> Directing attention with the voice and body.</li>\n<li><em>Repetition:</em> Repeating sounds, improvised words, or movements for emphasis.</li>\n<li><em>Vocal Tone:</em> Using different tones of voice to convey emotion (e.g., anger, fear, hope).</li>\n</ul><br><strong>Connection and Discussion</strong><br>Facilitate a class discussion connecting the devised theater work to Global Goal 16.<br>Ask guiding questions like:\n<ul>\n<li>How did we use our voices and movement to represent the ideas of peace and justice?</li>\n<li>Which movements or vocalizations were most effective in conveying a specific target of Global Goal 16?</li>\n<li>What did you notice about how the group worked together to create meaning through both action and sound?</li>\n<li>How can this way of creating theater help us understand complex social issues and give voice to different perspecives?</li>\n</ul><br><strong>Reflection and Summary</strong><br>Have students reflect on their learning experience through discussion or writing.<br>Ask guiding questions like:\n<ul>\n<li>How did using both movement and vocal improvisation in our devised theater explorations help you understand the complex concepts of peace, justice, and strong institutions?</li>\n<li>What did you learn about the power of combining physical actions with spontaneous words and sounds to convey emotions and ideas related to Global Goal 16?</li>\n<li>Did creating short theatrical pieces, exploring different stimuli, help you see the challenges or opportunities of building just societies in a new or more impactful way?</li>\n<li>What did you discover about your own capacity to express complex social issues through both your body and your voice in a collaborative setting?</li>\n<li>How can devised theater, which builds from the ground up, mirror the process of building inclusive communities or strengthening institutions?</li>\n<li>What new insights did you gain about Global Goal 16 and the importance of promoting peaceful and inclusive societies, providing access to justice, and building effective, accountable institutions?</li>\n<li>How did the various explorations (e.g., related to violence, corruption, legal identity, non-discrimination) illuminate the diverse facets and interconnectedness of Global Goal 16?</li>\n<li>Did the activity make you think differently about how different voices and perspectives (represented by our individual contributions) are crucial for addressing issues of justice and peace?</li>\n<li>What common themes or powerful messages about building a fairer world emerged across the different improvisations we explored?</li>\n<li>How does a theatrical approach help to humanize the abstract concepts of governance, policy, and human rights?</li>\n<li>Did any particular movement, vocalization, or collaborative moment from our explorations resonate with you personally regarding issues of peace, justice, or fairness?</li>\n<li>What emotions did you connect with during this lesson, and how might those emotions motivate you to take action related to Global Goal 16?</li>\n<li>What is one key takeaway about building justice and the power of collaborative creative expression that you will remember from this lesson?</li>\n<li>How has this lesson influenced your thinking about your own role in promoting peace and justice in your daily life or community?</li>\n</ul><br><strong>Assessment</strong>\n<ul>\n<li>Consistent and enthusiastic involvement in all phases of the lesson, including the introduction to devised theater, brainstorming stimuli, guided improvisations (both physical and vocal), and class discussions.</li>\n<li>Comprehension of Global Goal 16 themes (e.g., reducing violence, access to justice, strong institutions, human rights, anti-corruption) as demonstrated through the intention and content of the movement and vocal improvisations and verbal explanations during discussions.</li>\n<li>Originality and effectiveness in applying chosen devised theater elements (e.g., physical theater, vocalizations, improvised words/phrases, use of space/levels, rhythm) to explore and communicate messages related to Global Goal 16.</li>\n<li>How clearly and powerfully the collective improvisations communicated the understanding of specific aspects of Global Goal 16. Did the combined actions and sounds successfully evoke thought or emotion related to the goal?</li>\n<li>Ability to work effectively as a whole class, demonstrating active listening, responsive movement and vocalization, and a cohesive group dynamic during shared explorations. Look for willingness to build on others’ ideas.</li>\n<li>Comfort level in experimenting with spontaneous movement and vocalization, demonstrating a willingness to step out of the comfort zone for creative expression.</li>\n<li>Nuance and depth of understanding demonstrated in reflections, particularly concerning the role of embodied and vocal theater in understanding complex social issues and achieving peace and justice.</li>\n</ul>"} {sdgColor} />

